ds^2=\frac{dx^2+dy^2}{x^2}
x > 0
x^2+y^2=1
(\cos\alpha,\sin\alpha)
(\cos \beta, \sin\beta)
ds^2=\displaystyle\frac{d\theta^2}{\cos^2\theta}
\pi/3, -\pi/3
2\pi/3
4\pi/3=\sqrt{\displaystyle\frac{{(\pi/3-(-\pi/3))}^2}{cos^2{(\pi/3})}}
x^2 + y^2 = 1
(\cos \theta, \sin \theta)
x(\theta) = \cos \theta
y(\theta) = \sin \theta
ds^2 = \frac{dx^2+dy^2}{x^2} = \frac{(\sin^2\theta+\cos^2\theta) \, d\theta^2}{\cos^2\theta} = \sec^2\theta \, d\theta^2.
s = \int \sqrt{ds^2} = \int_{\alpha}^{\beta} |\sec \theta| \, d\theta \, . 
